---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Genitourinary Assessment – Health Assessment">
  <h1>Genitourinary Assessment</h1>
  <p><em>Head-to-Toe Assessment Component · Section 1: Health Assessment</em></p>
  <p>
    The genitourinary (GU) assessment evaluates kidney function and urinary output.
    Adequate urine output is a critical indicator of renal perfusion and overall
    hemodynamic status.
  </p>

  <h2 id="urine-output">Urine Output</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Minimum acceptable</strong></td><td>0.5 mL/kg/hr</td><td>Below this level indicates oliguria — inadequate renal perfusion</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Normal adult output</strong></td><td>30–50 mL/hr (720–1,500 mL/day)</td><td>Reflects adequate cardiac output and renal function</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Oliguria</strong></td><td>&lt;400 mL/day (&lt;30 mL/hr)</td><td>AKI, dehydration, shock, urinary obstruction</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Anuria</strong></td><td>&lt;100 mL/day</td><td>Severe renal failure, complete obstruction — emergent evaluation</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Polyuria</strong></td><td>&gt;2,500 mL/day</td><td>Diabetes insipidus, DM (uncontrolled), diuretic therapy, post-AKI diuresis</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Report Immediately</strong>
    Urine output &lt;30 mL/hr for 2 consecutive hours requires prompt notification.
    This may indicate evolving acute kidney injury (AKI) or hemodynamic compromise.
  </div>

  <h2 id="urine-color">Urine Color</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Color</th><th>Possible Cause</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Pale yellow / straw</td><td>Normal; well-hydrated</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Deep yellow / amber</td><td>Concentrated; dehydration; some vitamins (B2)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Orange</td><td>Pyridium (phenazopyridine), rifampin, severe dehydration, bilirubinuria</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pink / red</td><td>Hematuria (blood), beeturia, rifampin, myoglobinuria</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Brown / tea-colored</td><td>Myoglobinuria (rhabdomyolysis), severe hepatitis, bile pigments</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cloudy / milky</td><td>UTI (pyuria), chyluria, phosphaturia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dark brown or black</td><td>Severe hemolysis, melanoma, alkaptonuria — urgent</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="clarity">Clarity</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clear:</strong> Normal</li>
    <li><strong>Hazy/cloudy:</strong> Sediment, mucus, phosphates (may be normal in alkaline urine), or infection</li>
    <li><strong>Turbid:</strong> Pus cells (pyuria), bacteria — UTI likely</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="odor">Odor</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Faint/aromatic:</strong> Normal</li>
    <li><strong>Strong ammonia:</strong> Concentrated urine (dehydration); or bacteria decomposing urea (UTI)</li>
    <li><strong>Sweet/fruity:</strong> Ketones — DKA or starvation ketosis</li>
    <li><strong>Fecal:</strong> Fistula between bowel and bladder (vesico-enteric fistula)</li>
    <li><strong>Foul/putrid:</strong> UTI, especially with gram-negative organisms</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="symptoms">Patient-Reported Urinary Symptoms</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Description</th><th>Common Cause</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Dysuria</strong></td><td>Painful or burning urination</td><td>UTI, urethritis, STI</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Frequency</strong></td><td>Urinating more often than usual</td><td>UTI, OAB, diabetes, diuretics</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Urgency</strong></td><td>Sudden strong urge to urinate</td><td>UTI, overactive bladder, interstitial cystitis</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Hesitancy</strong></td><td>Difficulty starting stream</td><td>BPH, urethral stricture, neurogenic bladder</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Incontinence</strong></td><td>Involuntary loss of urine</td><td>Stress (coughing), urge, overflow, functional</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Nocturia</strong></td><td>Waking ≥2×/night to urinate</td><td>Heart failure (nocturnal diuresis), UTI, BPH, diabetes</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Hematuria</strong></td><td>Blood in urine (gross or microscopic)</td><td>UTI, kidney stones, trauma, cancer, anticoagulants</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="catheter-care">Catheter-Associated UTI (CAUTI) Prevention</h2>
  <p>When an indwelling urinary catheter is present:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Maintain a closed drainage system; keep the drainage bag below bladder level.</li>
    <li>Ensure tubing is free of kinks and patent.</li>
    <li>Perform meatal care with soap and water during daily bathing.</li>
    <li>Assess daily for catheter necessity — remove as soon as medically feasible.</li>
    <li>Document urine output, color, clarity, and odor every shift.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Fluid Balance Connection</strong>
    Urine output is a key component of fluid balance (I&amp;O monitoring). Ensure all fluid
    intake is documented accurately. 1 mL of urine ≈ 1 gram; 1 L = 1 kg of body weight.
  </div>
</Layout>
